Description of external morphology (NSMT E-13189).
Disc.
Circular, 
14.3 mm
in diameter (
Figs 2C–F
, 
3A
), surfaces completely covered by thick skin, and no external ossicles observed even when dried (
Fig. 3A–C
). Radial shields and their surrounds slightly tumid, bar-like, 6 to 7 times longer than wide, one third to half disc radius (
Fig. 3C
). On ventral surface, oral shields, adoral shields and oral plates completely covered by the thick skin (
Fig. 3D
). Oral shield serving as madreporite unrecognizable in external view (
Fig. 3D
). Interradial ventral disc covered also by skin (
Fig. 3E
). Genital slits long, almost extending to dorsal disc edge (
Fig. 3E, F
), approximately 
0.27 mm
in width (
Fig. 3E
). Two flat, subequal presumably infradental papillae and adoral shield spines and a spiniform oral plate ridge papilla just below the inner presumably infradental papilla at each opening for the second tentacle of adoral shield (
Fig. 3D
). More than 20 pointed tooth papillae on dental plate, forming 3 or 4 vertical rows (
Fig. 3D
). Second tentacle pore completely inside the mouth slit.

Proximal lateral arm plates (slightly distant from the base of the arm) higher than long, strongly arched, sickle-shaped, with pointed ventral-proximal and dorsal-proximal protru- sion, and strongly pointed on ventral-distal side (
Fig. 7B, C
). On inner surface, irregular series of perforations forming a vertical line on the center (
Fig. 7C
) and two well defined, confluent knobs lying on ventral side (
Fig. 7C
). Six to seven equal-sized spine articulations on distal edge (
Fig. 7B, D
), composed of parallel, horizontal and equal-sized dorsal and ventral lobes, with muscle and nerve openings inside lobes (
Fig. 7D
). A short ridge in proximal space between a pair of lobes (
Fig. 7B
). In middle portion of arm, proximal edge straight and distal edge rounded; positions of three spine articulations, confluent knobs and ridges almost same as those of proximal portion of arm but perforations unrecognizable (
Fig. 7E–G
). Spine articulations on distal edge (
Fig. 7E, G
), composed of parallel, horizontal and equal-sized dorsal and ventral lobes, with muscle and nerve openings inside lobes (
Fig. 7G
). Distal lateral arm plates elongated parallelograms with slightly pointed ventral-proximal and dorsal-proximal protrusions (
Fig. 7I
). On inner surface, a perforation recognizable centrally, no conspicuous ridge defined (
Fig. 7H
). Two equal-sized spine articulations on distal edge (
Fig. 7J
), composed of parallel, horizontal and equal-sized dorsal and ventral lobes, muscle and nerve openings unrecognizable (
Fig. 7J
). Arm spines long, flat and broad on proximal portion of arm (
Fig. 7K, L
). In middle arm portions, the middle spine cylindrical, while other ventral and dorsal spines still flat and broad (
Fig. 8A, B
); spines on distal portion of arm, spiniform (
Fig. 8C
). Adradial tentacle scales long, flat, thin, and gradually decreasing in size from proximal to distal (
Fig. 8D–F
) arm regions, abradial scales shorter and flatter than inner.

Proximal dorsal arm plates hexagonal, as long as wide, distal edge becoming rounder, and density of stereom structure coarser dorsally than ventrally (
Fig. 8G, H
). Middle dorsal arm plates also hexagonal but the lateral side acute, density of stereom almost the same on both dorsal and ventral sides (
Fig. 8H, I
). On distal portion of arm, dorsal arm plate rhomboid with rounded edge, longer than wide, pointing to proximal edge, similar in form to a water drop, density of stereom almost the same in dorsal and ventral sides (
Fig. 8K, L
). Ventral arm plates on proximal and middle portion of arm octagonal, spearhead-shaped, wider than long, with concave lateral edges (
Fig. 8M–P
), becoming spear shaped distally, pointing to distal side, with concave lateral edges (
Fig. 8Q, R
). Density of stereom structure coarser on dorsal side than ventral side (
Fig. 8M–R
).

A specimen fixed in ethanol for approximately 6 months (NSMT E-13189) displays almost the same color pattern as in its living state (
Fig. 2E, F
). In the fixed state, however, proximal-dorsal portion of arms are dark brown, except for the yellow bands.

Remarks . The examined species falls within the genus
Ophiopsila
by virtue of having extremely long tentacle scales that cross on the mid-line of the ventral side of arm; arm spine articulations of lateral arm plates with two smooth, parallel, straight lobes; a short ridge in proximal space between the lobes; inner side of the lateral arm plates with two merged knobs ( Guille and Jangoux 1978 ;
O’Hara et al. 2018
).
